"Bernie D., Lowe J., Tyrrell T., Legge O.","Influence of mitigation policy on ocean acidification",2010,"Geophysical Research Letters","37","15", L15704,"","",,,10.1029/2010GL043181,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77955483645&partnerID=40&md5=099ef1309293a435ac016430e303192a","Met Office Hadley Centre, Fitzroy Road, Exeter EX1 3PB, United Kingdom; Met Office Hadley Centre, Department of Meteorology, University of Reading, Earley Gate, Reading RG6 6BB, United Kingdom; National Oceanography Centre, Southampton, University of Southampton, Waterfront Campus, European Way, Southampton SO14 3ZH, United Kingdom","Bernie, D., Met Office Hadley Centre, Fitzroy Road, Exeter EX1 3PB, United Kingdom; Lowe, J., Met Office Hadley Centre, Department of Meteorology, University of Reading, Earley Gate, Reading RG6 6BB, United Kingdom; Tyrrell, T., National Oceanography Centre, Southampton, University of Southampton, Waterfront Campus, European Way, Southampton SO14 3ZH, United Kingdom; Legge, O., National Oceanography Centre, Southampton, University of Southampton, Waterfront Campus, European Way, Southampton SO14 3ZH, United Kingdom","This study quantifies the relative impact on future ocean acidification of different aspects of global climate change mitigation policies, such as the year that global emissions peak, how fast they reduce after their peak, and the long term minimum emissions that are possible. Relative to a scenario where emissions peak in 2016 and then decrease by 1% per year, further emissions reductions to 2, 3 and 4% per year lead to the same impact minimum pH (by 2100) if emissions peak 10, 15 and 17 years later respectively. Over the same time scale, non-mitigation scenarios lead to a decrease of global mean surface pH of 7.67 to 7.81. Strong and urgent mitigation, emissions peaking in 2016 and reducing by 5% per year, are shown to limit this minimum to 8.02. Minimum pH over longer timescales, the next 500 years, is largely determined by the minimum emission level that is attainable, owing to its relation with cumulative emissions.",,"Oceanography; Emission level; Emissions reduction; Global climate changes; Global emissions; Long term; Mitigation policies; Relative impact; Time-scales; Climate change; acidification; emission control; environmental impact; environmental policy; global climate; marine pollution; pH; timescale",,,,,,"Allen, M.R., Warming caused by cumulative carbon emissions towards the trillionth tonne (2009) Nature, 458, pp. 1163-1166. , doi:10.1038/nature08019; Caldeira, K., Wickett, M., Ocean model predictions of chemistry changes from carbon dioxide emissions to the atmosphere and ocean (2005) Journal of Geophysical Research C: Oceans, 110 (9), pp. 1-12. , DOI 10.1029/2004JC002671, C09S04; Canadell, J.G., Le Quere, C., Raupach, M.R., Field, C.B., Buitenhuis, E.T., Ciais, P., Conway, T.J., Marland, G., Contributions to accelerating atmospheric CO<inf>2</inf> growth from economic activity, carbon intensity, and efficiency of natural sinks (2007) Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America, 104 (47), pp. 18866-18870. , http://www.pnas.org/cgi/reprint/104/47/18866, DOI 10.1073/pnas.0702737104; Cao, L., Caldeira, K., Atmospheric CO<inf>2</inf> stabilization and ocean acidification (2008) Geophys. Res. Lett., 35, pp. L19609. , doi:10.1029/2008GL035072; Cao, L., Caldeira, K., Jain, A.K., Effects of carbon dioxide and climate change on ocean acidification and carbonate mineral saturation (2007) Geophysical Research Letters, 34 (5), pp. L05607. , DOI 10.1029/2006GL028605; Chuck, A., Tyrrell, T., Totterdell, I.J., Holligan, P.M., The oceanic response to carbon emissions over the next century: Investigation using three ocean carbon cycle models (2005) Tellus, Series B: Chemical and Physical Meteorology, 57 (1), pp. 70-86. , DOI 10.1111/j.1600-0889.2005.00127.x; Cox, P.M., Description of the TRIFFID dynamic global vegetation model (2001) Tech. Note 24, Met Off